n urban life at the time. Soares analyzes the role that Catholicism, and particularly lay brotherhoods, played in Africans' construction of identities under slavery in colonial Brazil. As in the rest of the Portuguese empire, black lay brotherhoods in Rio engaged in expressions of imperial pomp through elaborate festivals, processions, and funerals; the election of kings and queens; and the organization of royal courts. Drawing mainly on ecclesiastical documents, Soares reveals the value of church records for historical research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAfricansxReligious lifezBrazilzRio de Janeiro. 0aAfricanszBrazilzRio de JaneiroxEthnic identity. 0aSlaveryzBrazilzRio de JaneiroxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlavesxReligious lifezBrazilzRio de Janeiro. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aMetz, Jerry Dennis08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394303zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394303.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles